{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532296"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:24:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:24:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.11,0.03,0.12,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110086"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"3625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110086"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive right knee pain and swelling. He reports fevers and rigors. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a carpenter and denies any recent trauma or injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His right knee is warm, swollen, and extremely tender with a reduced range of movement. Joint aspiration reveals turbid fluid with white cell count 85,000 \u00d7 10\u2076/L (\u0026gt;90% neutrophils). Gram stain shows gram-positive cocci in clusters.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate empiric antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flucloxacillin","Vancomycin","Gentamicin","Ceftriaxone","Benzylpenicillin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with septic arthritis of the knee, with gram-positive cocci in clusters on microscopy, which is consistent with \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. The presence of fever, joint pain, swelling, and markedly elevated synovial fluid white cell count confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate empiric therapy as it provides excellent coverage against methicillin-sensitive \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MSSA), which is the most common causative organism in native joint septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate as monotherapy as it does not cover penicillinase-producing \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, which accounts for most community-acquired staphylococcal infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is not the first-line therapy for gram-positive cocci in clusters, but is the empiric agent of choice for suspected gram-negative septic arthritis, such as that caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae or Escherichia coli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inappropriate as it does not provide adequate coverage against gram-positive organisms, which are the most common causes of septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be reserved for cases where methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) is suspected, such as in healthcare-associated infections or in patients with known MRSA colonisation. It is not first-line therapy in this community-acquired case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flucloxacillin is the first-line therapy for septic arthritis caused by Staphylococcus aureus, unless methicillin-resistant strains are suspected or confirmed.","Joint aspiration for culture and microscopy should be performed before starting antibiotics when possible."],"references":["Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {26 Oct 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Momodu II, Savaliya V. Septic Arthritis. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538176/","Earwood JS, Walker TR, Sue GJC. Septic Arthritis: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Dec 1;104(6):589-597. PMID: 34913662. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34913662/","Sanpera I, Salom M, Alves C, Eastwood D. Diagnosis and management of septic arthritis: A current concepts review. J Child Orthop. 2025 Jan 2;19(1):14-19. doi: 10.1177/18632521241311302. PMID: 39758603; PMCID: PMC11694264. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39758603/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T08:08:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T08:08:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7359"}},"content":